'''Albert Pallavicini''' ({{lang-it|Alberto Pallavicini}}) was the fifth [[marquess of Bodonitsa]] from his father's death until his own in 1311. His father was [[Thomas Pallavicini|Thomas]], a great-nephew of the first marquess, [[Guy Pallavicini|Guy]]. Albert married [[Maria dalle Carceri]], a [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] noblewoman from [[Euboea]]. He even obtained [[Triarchy of Negroponte|a sixth]] of that island.

He was a loyal vassal of the [[Prince of Achaea|princes of Achaea]]. In 1305, he was summoned by his lord [[Philip I of Piedmont|Philip of Savoy]] to a [[tournament]] and [[parliament]] on the [[Isthmus of Corinth]]. In 1307, he obeyed the similar summons of [[Philip I of Taranto]]. On 15 March 1311, he followed [[Walter V of Brienne]] into the [[Battle of the Cephissus]], but did not emerge alive. By the ''[[Assizes of Romania]]'', his fief was inherited by his widow and his daughter, [[Guglielma Pallavicini|Guglielma]].

