'''Dr. Benjamin Hayes Dougan''' (June 22, 1867 - January 1, 1940) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[physician]] and [[politician]] in the [[New Brunswick|Province of New Brunswick]]. Known by his middle name, in the [[Canada 1901 Census|1901 Canadian census]], he is listed as Hazen Dugan. At census time, he was at his future in-laws home in [[Gagetown, New Brunswick]]. In 1906, he married Blanch M. Slipp (1878–1959).

Dougan became a medical doctor and he and his wife made their home in [[Harvey Station, New Brunswick]]. In 1924, he gained wide recognition as the Province's [[coroner]] who conducted the inquiry into the sensational shooting deaths of two young female siblings in [[Fosterville, New Brunswick]]. Capitalizing on his celebrity following the January 1925 trial and conviction of [[Darius H. Thornton]] for the double murders, in the August [[New Brunswick general election, 1925|provincial election]] Dougan was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of New Brunswick]] as the [[Progressive Conservative Party of New Brunswick|Conservative Party]] candidate in the multiple-member riding of [[York County, New Brunswick|New Brunswick]]. He was reelected in [[New Brunswick general election, 1930|1930]] and served until June 27, 1939.

Benjamin Hayes Dougan died in 1940. He and his wife are buried in the [[Fredericton Rural Cemetery]].

