{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country= |Ship flag= |Ship name=''Cornelia B. Windiate'' |Ship operator= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=Windiate & Butler, Manitowoc |Ship yard number= |Ship laid down=1874 |Ship launched= |Ship completed= |Ship acquired= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship fate=Sank 1875 |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship tonnage=322 |Ship displacement= |Ship length= |Ship beam= |Ship height= |Ship draught= |Ship draft= |Ship ice class= |Ship sail plan= |Ship propulsion= |Ship speed= |Ship capacity= |Ship crew= |Ship notes= }} |}
The '''''Cornelia B. Windiate''''' was a schooner that sank in 1875 with all hands, presumably in Lake Michigan near the [[Straits of Mackinac]]. The ship was eastbound from [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin|Milwaukee]] to [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]. The reason for her sinking is unknown, but she departed November 27, late in the season, and was overloaded with grain<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seahistory.org/assets/KIDS-121-35.pdf |title=Great Lakes Ghost Ship: the Cornelia B. Windiate |accessdate=2017-07-28}}</ref>.
In 1986 The Windiate was discovered by divers in Lake Huron, near [[Alpena, Michigan]], further east than expected. The wreck is unique in that her cargo is still secure in her holds which is quite unusual for a wreck. Her masts are still standing with rigging <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thunderbaywrecks.com/3d-wreck-cornelia-b-windiate.php |title=Cornelia B Windiate Wreck |accessdate=2017-07-28}}</ref>.
