{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}} {{Use British English|date=May 2016}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Oliver Brown | image = | caption = | fullname = Oliver Maurice Brown | birth_date = {{birth date|1908|10|10|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Burton upon Trent]], England | death_date = {{death year and age|1953|1908}} | death_place = London, England | height = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}<ref name=WhosWho37/> | position = [[Forward (association football)|Centre forward]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = – | clubs1 = Trent Villa | caps1 = | goals1 = | years2 = – | clubs2 = Robirth Athletic | caps2 = | goals2 = | years3 = – | clubs3 = [[Burton Town F.C.|Burton Town]] | caps3 = | goals3 = | years4 = 1930–1931 | clubs4 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] | caps4 = 9 | goals4 = 6 | years5 = 1931–1933 | clubs5 = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] | caps5 = 51 | goals5 = 33 | years6 = 1933 | clubs6 = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] | caps6 = 0 | goals6 = 0 | years7 = 1933–1937 | clubs7 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] | caps7 = 58 | goals7 = 38 }} '''Oliver Maurice Brown''' (10 October 1908 – 1953), also known as '''Buster Brown''',<ref name=WhosWho37>{{cite book |first1=Tim |last1=Carder |first2=Roger |last2=Harris |title=Albion A–Z: A Who's Who of Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. |year=1997 |publisher=Goldstone Books |location=Hove |page=37 |isbn=0-9521337-1-7}}</ref> was an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who scored 77 goals from 118 appearances in [[the Football League]] playing as a [[Forward (association football)|centre forward]] for [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] and [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref name=Joyce>{{cite book |last=Joyce |first=Michael |title=Football League Players' Records 1888 to 1939 |publisher=SoccerData (Tony Brown) |location=Nottingham |year=2004 |page=39 |isbn=978-1-899468-67-6}}</ref> He was Brighton's top scorer in the 1933–34 and 1934–35 seasons with, respectively, 15 and 26 goals in all competitions.<ref>Carden & Harris, p. 338.</ref>
Brown was born in [[Burton upon Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], and died in London. His younger brother [[Ambrose Brown|Ambrose]] was also a professional footballer who played League football for [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]], [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] and [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]].<ref name=WhosWho37/><ref>Joyce, p. 38.</ref>
