{{Refimprove|date=August 2018}} {{Infobox saint |name=Venerable Thomas Belchiam |birth_date=unknown |death_date={{death date|1537|8|3|df=y}} |feast_day= |venerated_in=[[Roman Catholicism]] |image= |imagesize= |caption= |birth_place= |death_place= [[England]] |titles=Greenwich Franciscan Martyr of England |beatified_date= |beatified_place= |beatified_by=Pope [[Leo XIII]] |canonized_date= |canonized_place= |canonized_by= |attributes= |patronage= |major_shrine= |suppressed_date= |issues= |prayer="In Thee, O Lord, have I put my trust; let me never be confounded." |prayer_attrib= }}
'''Venerable Thomas Belchiam''' (1508–1537) was an English [[Franciscan]] who died in [[Newgate Prison]] in the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]. He is a Catholic [[martyr]], declared venerable by [[Pope Leo XIII]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattlecatholic.com/a050727.html|title=The Observant Friar Martyrs of Greenwich (Seattle Catholic)|website=www.seattlecatholic.com}}</ref> The year of death is in question: the ''[[Victoria County History]]'' for Kent puts the events in 1534.<ref name=Kent>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=38219|title=Friaries: The observant friars of Greenwich - British History Online|website=www.british-history.ac.uk}}</ref> It references [[Thomas Bourchier (Franciscan)|Thomas Bourchier]]'s ''Historia Ecclesiastica de Martyrio Fratrum...'', "though the writer assigns them to 1537".<ref name=Kent/> Dom [[Bede Camm]], O.S.B., places Belchiam's date of death as August 3, 1537.<ref name=Camm>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/02394b.htm Camm, Bede. "Ven. Thomas Belchiam." The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 2. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1907. 3 August 2018</ref> ''Notes and Queries'' lists him as dying in 1538.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2wo4AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA23&lpg=PA23&dq=Thomas+Belchiam&source=bl&ots=kdErA1aOg5&sig=Q9fAOryRG7O9luj3GOvBSO7eo-E&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjajK_BwtLcAhXM24MKHTTIB3s4ChDoATAAegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=Thomas%20Belchiam&f=false ''Notes and Queries'', London, John Francis, 1882, p. 23]</ref>
==Life== Belchiam was a friar of the convent at [[Greenwich]]. He was imprisoned, with other Franciscans, for refusing to take the [[Acts of Supremacy|oath of the royal supremacy]], and declaring the king to be a [[heresy|heretic]]. He was considered an accomplished prescher, and wrote a sermon on the text, 'Behold, they that wear soft clothing are in kings' houses' (Matt. xi. 8), in which he lashed the vices of the court and the avarice and inconstancy of the clergy.<ref name=Camm/> At the intercession of [[Thomas Wriothesley]] some of the friars were released. Belchiam was kept in Newgate, where he died of starvation on 3 August 1537. Belchiam survived the last of his two fellow-prisoners upwards of a month, he likely being the youngest. As he lay dying, "...it so fell out that the frame of the earth gave a surprising shock, that the jail keepers were affrighted, and it was thought to be a universal earthquake...It is said that the king gave orders for the burial of Belchiam, his majesty being startled at the uncommon accidents that happened at his departure out of this life."<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mIgwAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=Thomas+Belchiam&source=bl&ots=McW44ZfFiR&sig=99P6iJdlHFndlY5gGWPs8YWkWzs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjajK_BwtLcAhXM24MKHTTIB3s4ChDoATAEegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=Thomas%20Belchiam&f=false ''Modern British Martyrology'', Keating, Brown, 1836, p. 87{{PD-notice}}]</ref>
A copy of his sermon, found in the prison after his death, was brought to Henry VIII, who was affected by it, but had it burnt. Another copy was preserved by the friars, and [[Thomas Bourchier (Franciscan)|Thomas Bourchier]], writing in 1583, expressed a hope that it might be published; which apparently was never done.
